question.title: What will be the Republican advantage (or disadvantage) vs Democrats in the House of Representatives after the 2026 elections?
question.description:
Every 2 years, the United States elects all 435 members of the [House of Representatives](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_House_of_Representatives), as well as one-third of the 100 members of the [Senate](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Senate). As of October 2025, Republicans hold a slim majority of 219 seats in the House, one of 53 seats in the Senate, and the Presidency. Recent decades have been [highly competitive](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Senate#/media/File:Combined--Control_of_the_U.S._House_of_Representatives_-_Control_of_the_U.S._Senate.png). In the [last 10 midterm elections](https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/statistics/data/seats-congress-gainedlost-the-presidents-party-mid-term-elections), the party opposing the President gained a median of 11 seats in the House, and gained at least one seat in 8 out of 10 years.

[The election](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2026_United_States_House_of_Representatives_elections) is currently scheduled for November 3, 2026.
question.resolution_criteria: This question will resolve as the number of seats won by Republicans minus the number of seats won by Democrats in the US House of Representantives at the 2026 midterm elections.
question.fine_print:
* Independent or third-party candidates who are known to caucus with one party will be included in the count for the relevant party.
* If the Democrats win more seats than the Republicans, this question will resolve as a negative number.
* This number will be determined by whomever won their elections, following any runoff elections or recounts, according to credible sources. It will not necessarily reflect the House Membership or party control at any particular time (e.g., if members retire or are appointed during the counting and resolution of votes).
